CEO and Deputy CEO observations
DBS Group Holdings
4Q 2024 financial results
February 10, 2025
Disclaimer: The information contained in this document is intended only for use during the presentation and should not be disseminated or distributed to parties outside the presentation.
DBS Bank accepts no liability whatsoever with respect to the use of this document or its contents.

Operating trends sustained in 4Q

Strong fourth quarter caps record year
4Q total income up 10% YoY from broad-based growth
o

Healthy loan demand
Growth led by non-trade corporate loans, partially offset by high repayments
o

Lower deposit costs from rate cuts and Casa inflows

Group NIM rises 4bp QoQ to 2.15%
Lower funding cost and accounting asymmetry for markets trading more than
o
offset commercial book NIM decline of 6bp due to lower interest rates
NII up 4% from higher NIM and balance sheet growth
o
2

Operating trends sustained in 4Q

Strong wealth management momentum sustained
Fees and treasury customer sales growth led by wealth management
o
NNM sustained around recent quarter levels, AUM at new high
o

Expense growth well managed, cost-income ratio stable YoY

Asset quality sound
Higher 4Q SP due to lower recoveries and repayments
o
3

2025 outlook

Group net interest income slightly above 2024 levels based on two rate cuts in 2H25
Slight decline in Group NIM, offset by loan growth
o
Markets trading to benefit from lower funding cost
o

Commercial book non-interest income growth to be high-single digits
Led by growth in wealth management fees and treasury customer sales
o

Cost-income ratio to be in low-40% range

SP assumed to normalise to 17-20bp
Potential for GP writebacks
o

Pretax profit to be around 2024 levels

Net profit to be below 2024 levels due to global minimum tax of 15%
4

Distributing our earnings to stakeholders

Shareholders
Quarterly ordinary dividend per share increase of 6 cents to 60 cents from 4Q,
o
bringing annualised ordinary dividend per share going forward to $2.40
Board committed to managing down excess capital over the coming three years
o
Capital Return dividend of 15 cents per share per quarter planned for financial year
o
2025

Community
Another contribution of $100 million as part of ten-year $1 billion commitment to
o
support vulnerable segments

Employees
Special one-time bonus of SGD 1,0001 each to be paid to all staff except senior
o
managers as additional reward for contribution to record performance
1/ Indexed to purchasing power parity in markets outside Singapore
